<DOCID> wsj94_004.0015 </DOCID>
<DOCNO> 940425-0043. </DOCNO>
<HL>    Business Brief -- Armco Inc.:
@  Steelmaker to Cut 200 Jobs
@  In Its Salaried Work Force </HL>
<DD> 04/25/94 </DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3 </SO>
<CO>    AS </CO>
<IN> STEEL MANUFACTURERS (STL) </IN>
<TXT>
<p>
   Armco Inc. said it will cut about 200 salaried positions, or 3%
of its total work force, in an effort to eliminate redundancies
between corporate and plant administrative positions.
</p>
<p>
   The specialty steelmaker projected that the cuts would save about
$15 million a year after they're completed in the fall.
</p>
<p>
   At its annual meeting, Armco also named John C. Haley, 64 years
old, chairman. Mr. Haley's appointment is for a one-year term,
during which Armco's board will study the concept of a nonexecutive
chairman. Mr. Haley, an Armco board member since 1975, is retired
chairman and chief executive officer of closely held Business
International Corp. He succeeds Robert L. Purdum, 58, who retired.
</p>
<p>
   In addition, Armco named Bruce E. Robbins, 49, and John D.
Turner, 48, to its board. Mr. Robbins is president and chief
executive officer of PNC Bank N.A., a unit of PNC Bank Corp. Mr.
Turner is president and chief executive of Copperweld Corp.
</p>
<p>
   With Mr. Purdum's retirement, Armco's board now has nine members.
</p>
</TXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> wsj94_004.0180 </DOCID>
<DOCNO> 940422-0086. </DOCNO>
<HL>    Business Brief -- Cheyenne Software Inc.:
@  Fiscal Third-Quarter Profit
@  Rose 82%, Shares Rebound </HL>
<DD> 04/22/94 </DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8 </SO>
<CO>    CYE </CO>
<IN> SOFTWARE (SOF) </IN>
<TXT>
<p>
   Cheyenne Software Inc.'s shares rebounded 13% on news of higher
earnings, as the company announced its chairman would step down.
</p>
<p>
   Shares of the Roslyn Heights, N.Y., developer of
automated-software solutions closed up $3 at $25.75 on the American
Stock Exchange after the company said fiscal third-quarter net rose
82% to $10.3 million, or 26 cents a share, from $5.6 million, or 14
cents a share, a year ago. Revenue rose 92% to $27.1 million for the
quarter ended March 31.
</p>
<p>
   The stock had been volatile after the CNBC cable-television
network reported concerns about its price, the company's products
and selling by corporate insiders. The company denied that a
management shakeup was imminent.
</p>
<p>
   Eli Oxenhorn, chairman since 1987, will step down to pursue other
interests, but will maintain a consulting role for three years.
ReiJane Huai, president, will succeed Mr. Oxenhorn, effective May
20.
</p>
</TXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> wsj94_005.0213 </DOCID>
<DOCNO> 940420-0087. </DOCNO>
<HL>    Who's News:
@  Federated Stores
@  Gave Questrom
@  Big Discount, Pay
@  ----
@  By Patrick M. Reilly
@  Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal </HL>
<DD> 04/20/94 </DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4 </SO>
<CO>    FD </CO>
<IN> BROADLINE RETAILERS (RTB) </IN>
<DATELINE> NEW YORK </DATELINE>
<TXT>
<p>
   Allen Questrom, chairman and chief executive officer
of Federated Department Stores Inc., certainly likes to shop where
he works.
</p>
<p>
   According to the proxy statement from the department store chain,
based in Cincinnati, Ohio, Mr. Questrom's salary and an additional
cash payment remained unchanged at $2 million for fiscal 1993, one
of the highest in general retailing. But his compensation also
included a whopping $168,301 in an "executive discount" on
merchandise purchased at Federated's stores, which include
Bloomingdale's, Burdines and Rich's, among others. A company
spokeswoman said Mr. Questrom took similar discounts in fiscal 1992.
</p>
<p>
   The spokeswoman said that, like executives at other retailers,
top Federated executives get a discount of roughly 40% off the
suggested retail price. She said that "a large portion" of the
purchases likely went to furnishing an old farmhouse in Connecticut,
which the flamboyant Mr. Questrom and his wife are restoring and
adding on to.
</p>
<p>
   Federated has been a solid performer under Mr. Questrom. In the
fiscal year ended Jan. 29, profit before charges grew about 48% to
$196.8 million. Under Mr. Questrom, Federated also bought a chunk of
R.H. Macy & Co. senior debt. Federated is now in talks with Macy
creditors on a reorganization plan that would merge the two chains.
</p>
<p>
   Mr. Questrom signed one of the richest contracts in retailing in
1990. The proxy noted that Mr. Questrom was paid $2 million for
signing on as Federated chairman and is guaranteed both a $1.2
million salary and $800,000 "value-added payment" for each year of
his five-year contract. When his contract is up Feb. 2, 1995, he'll
be entitled to another payment based on any increase in Federated's
stock price during his five-year reign.
</p>
<p>
   Other Federated executives received smaller bonuses, which are
tied to the company's operating-profit level and "individual
performances" of executives. James Zimmerman, president and chief
operating officer, received a $1 million salary, but his bonus
dropped to $232,800 from $310,400 in fiscal 1992. He took $19,321 in
executive discounts.
</p>
<p>
   The salary of Ron Tysoe, Federated vice chairman and chief
financial officer, remained at $650,000, but his bonus dropped to
$185,7000 from $247,600 in 1992. He received $22,963 in shopping
discounts and $16,116 for a car allowance.
</p>
