<HL>    E-Systems' Keiffer
@  Steps Down as CEO;
@  Lawson Assumes Post </HL>
<DD> 01/28/94 </DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5 </SO>
<CO>    ESY </CO>
<IN> AEROSPACE (ARO) </IN>
<DATELINE> DALLAS </DATELINE>
<TXT>
<p>
   E-Systems Inc. said E. Gene Keiffer stepped down as
chief executive officer and intends to retire in August as chairman.
</p>
<p>
   The defense-electronics concern named its president and chief
operating officer, A. Lowell Lawson, to succeed Mr. Keiffer as CEO.
The company said Mr. Lawson, 56 years old, is also expected to
succeed Mr. Keiffer as chairman. Mr. Keiffer, 64, is to remain on
the board after his retirement as chairman.
</p>
<p>
   The company also said it named Brian D. Cullen a senior vice
president, in addition to his duties as president and general
manager of E-Systems' largest division, located in Greenville,
Texas. Mr. Cullen, 53, will share operational responsibilities with
two other senior vice presidents, Terry Heil, 55, and Peter Marino,
51.
</p>
<p>
   Industry analysts said Mr. Keiffer's departure as chief executive
wasn't unexpected and they generally praised the company's moves.
"The biggest positive is the nice continuity," said Howard Rubel, an
analyst at Goldman, Sachs & Co.
</p>
<p>
   In a news release, Mr. Keiffer said the management changes were
designed to facilitate an orderly transition and streamline
management at a time when the defense contractor is seeking to
expand into lines of business unrelated to defense.
</p>
<p>
   Separately, E-Systems yesterday reported fourth-quarter net
income of $31.9 million, or 93 cents a share, up 9% from $29.3
million, or 88 cents a share, a year earlier. Analysts had projected
earnings of between 94 cents and 99 cents a share. Revenue fell
5.6%, to $523.6 million, from $554.9 million.
</p>
<p>
   In composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange Thursday,
E-Systems shares closed at $44.625, down 87.5 cents.
</p>
</TXT>
