<HL>    Business Brief -- Dollar Time Group Inc.:
@  Company Ends Pact to Buy
@  A Real New York Bargain </HL>
<DD> 01/14/94 </DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION </SO>
<CO>    DLRT </CO>
<IN> LIMITED PRODUCT SPECIALTY RETAILERS (OTS),
   ALL SPECIALTY RETAILERS (RTS) </IN>
<TXT>
<p>
   Dollar Time Group Inc. said it ended its agreement to acquire A
Real New York Bargain, a privately held retailer based in New York,
in a transaction originally valued at $43.6 million.
</p>
<p>
   Dollar Time, a Hollywood, Fla., operator of 55 variety stores,
said the two companies disagreed on the direction of Dollar Time's
operations. Moreover, Dollar Time, in a statement, said it had
become "concerned" about the profitability of A Real New York
Bargain since the two sides agreed to join forces in November.
</p>
<p>
   As part of the original agreement, Joseph Sasson, chief executive
officer of A Real New York Bargain, and Jeffrey Klansky, president
of the retailer, became chief executive and president, respectively,
of Dollar Time, as well as directors. Yesterday, the two men
resigned their positions at Dollar Time.
</p>
<p>
   Dollar Time said Gary de Luca, 40 years old, the company's chief
operating officer, was named president.
</p>
</TXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> wsj94_043.0269 </DOCID>
<DOCNO> 940112-0011. </DOCNO>
<HL>    Who's News:
@  Detroit Edison Names
@  Lilco's A.F. Earley
@  To Three Positions </HL>
<DD> 01/12/94 </DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7 </SO>
<CO>    DTE </CO>
<IN> ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC), CENTRAL U.S. ELECTRIC UTILITIES (UEC) </IN>
<DATELINE> DETROIT </DATELINE>
<TXT>
<p>
   Anthony F. Earley Jr., credited with recouping some
losses associated with another utility's failed nuclear plant, was
named president, chief operating officer and a director of Detroit
Edison Co., effective March 1.
</p>
<p>
   Prior to becoming president in 1989 of Long Island Lighting Co.,
Hicksville, N.Y., Mr. Earley, 44 years old, served as Lilco's
general counsel and was widely credited with steering the company
through the Shoreham nuclear-plant controversy. The utility decided
to close the facility in the face of mounting controversy and
litigation. Mr. Earley helped negotiate a deal with the state that
enabled Lilco to recoup most of its investment in Shoreham through a
series of rate increases through the 1990s.
</p>
<p>
   Because of his successes at Lilco, some analysts considered him
the heir apparent to William J. Catacosinos, 63, Lilco's chairman
and chief executive.
</p>
<p>
   "I'm surprised he's leaving when he could have been CEO in a few
years," said Barry M. Abramson, an analyst with Prudential
Securities Group Inc. "Maybe he can use his expertise in nuclear
issues at the Fermi plant, which seems very important to Detroit
Edison."
</p>
<p>
   His appointment comes as Detroit Edison is assessing the damages
caused last month by a fire at its Fermi 2 nuclear power plant in
Monroe, Mich. The company has said the resulting shutdown at the
plant could affect 1994 earnings.
</p>
<p>
   John E. Lobbia, 52, who formerly held the position of Detroit
Edison president, will continue as chairman and chief executive
officer of the utility.
</p>
<p>
   A spokeswoman for Lilco said the company would announce
succession plans for Mr. Earley's position at a later date.
</p>
</TXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> wsj94_044.0048 </DOCID>
<DOCNO> 940111-0056. </DOCNO>
<HL>    Business Brief -- McCormick & Co.:
@  Net Income Rose by 16%
@  During the Fourth Quarter </HL>
<DD> 01/11/94 </DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4 </SO>
<CO>    MCCRK </CO>
<IN> FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD), FOOD PRODUCERS, EXCLUDING FISHING (OFP) </IN>
<TXT>
<p>
   McCormick & Co., Sparks, Md., said fourth-quarter net income rose
16%, due to strength in its international, industrial and packaging
operations.
</p>
<p>
   Net for the quarter ended Nov. 30 rose to $40.5 million, or 50
cents a share, from the year-earlier $35 million, or 43 cents a
share. Sales rose 1.9% to $460.8 million from $452.2 million.
</p>
<p>
   Fourth-quarter results include a charge of two cents a share, or
$1.2 million, due to an increase in the federal corporate tax rate
and post-retirement benefits.
</p>
<p>
   Bailey Thomas, the spice company's chairman and chief executive
officer, said the company had a successful year despite onion costs,
unfavorable foreign-exchange rates, and weak economic conditions in
many markets. "We expect 1994 to be another good year," he said.
</p>
<p>
   For the full year, net income fell 23% to $73 million or 89 cents
a share, from the year-earlier $95.2 million, or $1.16 a share. The
latest year includes a $26.6 million, or 33 cent a share, charge for
cumulative effects of accounting changes. Sales rose 5.7% to $1.56
billion from $1.47 billion.
</p>
</TXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> wsj94_044.0296 </DOCID>
<DOCNO> 940107-0170. </DOCNO>
<HL>    Mariner Health Set
@  To Acquire Pinnacle
@  Through Stock Swap </HL>
<DD> 01/07/94 </DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4 </SO>
<CO>    MRNR </CO>
<IN> HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS (HEA) </IN>
<DATELINE> MYSTIC, Conn. </DATELINE>
<TXT>
<p>
   Mariner Health Group Inc. said it signed a
definitive agreement to acquire Pinnacle Care Corp. in a stock swap
valued at about $104 million.
</p>
<p>
   The deal would effectively double Mariner's revenue and extend
its geographic reach, the company said.
</p>
<p>
   Mariner, which expects to post revenue of about $70 million for
1993, provides subacute health care to patients who no longer
require the extensive services of an acute-care hospital but are too
sick to go home. Closely held Pinnacle, based in Nashville, Tenn.,
owns or manages 13 skilled nursing centers, operates 27 outpatient
rehabilitation clinics and contracts services to nursing homes. It's
expected to post revenue of about $70 million for 1993, Mariner
said.
</p>
<p>
   The pact is the latest in a series of combinations in the
health-care industry as providers move to position themselves for
the Clinton administration's proposed reforms. On Wednesday, Sun
Healthcare Inc., a nursing-home operator, agreed to acquire Mediplex
Group Inc., a provider of subacute care, for about $312 million in
cash and stock.
</p>
<p>
   Arthur W. Stratton Jr., chief executive officer and president of
Mariner, said the acquisition will extend Mariner's operations from
New England and mid-Atlantic states to the Southeastern region,
where Pinnacle has a strong presence.
</p>
<p>
   Under the agreement, Mariner said it will issue between 4.9
million and 5.5 million shares based on the price of Mariner's stock
before the transaction is completed. The $104 million acquisition
price is based on the $21.50 closing price of Mariner's shares in
Nasdaq trading yesterday. The company said it would issue 4.9
million shares based on that price.
</p>
<p>
   Pinnacle's management team will remain with the combined entity,
while Pinnacle's president and chief executive, J. George Harris,
will assume the positions of president and chief operating officer
of the new company. Dr. Stratton will remain chairman and chief
executive of Mariner.
</p>
<p>
   The acquisition has been approved by the boards of each company,
but still requires regulatory clearance and shareholder approvals.
The transaction is expected to be completed in April.
</p>
<p>
   Announcement of the planned acquisition was made after the stock
market closed yesterday; Mariner's shares were unchanged at $21.50.
</p>
</TXT>
</DOC>
